1.1

Create a regression RBF model with gamma equal 5. Plot the final hypothesis curve along with the training points on the same plot.

Computing the RBF matrix and weights

rbf_mat = function(x, u, gamma){
  mat = matrix(nrow=length(x), ncol=length(u))
  for (c in 1:length(u)){
    for (r in 1:length(x)){
      mat[r, c] = exp(-gamma*abs(x[r] - u[c])^2)
    }
  }
  return(mat)
}

x = vizData$x
y = vizData$y
mat = rbf_mat(x, x, 5)

Ws = solve(mat)%*%y

cat('Weights: ', Ws)
## Weights:  -0.3395237 0.345409 -0.2858542 0.5771596 0.3000221

Hypothesis curve

s = seq(min(vizData$x), max(vizData$x), length.out=100)

hx = function(matrix, ws){
  hhat = matrix %*% ws
  return(hhat)
}

unseen = rbf_mat(s, x, 5)
hxs = hx(unseen, Ws)

plot(s, hxs, type='l', col='blue')
points(x, y)

1.3

Explain your observations.

As gamma decreases, the hypothesis curve becomes smoother, while as gamma increases, the hypothesis curve gets bumpier as the function approaches each point. This is likely because the gamma level controls how much of an impact each input value has on the output value. Gamma acts as a scalar, so a smaller gamma will allow further input points to influence the hypothesis output more, where as a larger gamma level will limit the effect of further input points on the hypothesis output. This is why the RBF takes the form of a Gaussian, with the x axis as the distance between an input and a center and the y axis as the impact on the hypothesis output of a point at that distance. Gamma makes the gaussian wider if it is smaller, and skinnier if it is larger.

Problem 2 (20 points)

In this problem you will use the data file kMeansData.csv (x1 and x2 denote the input features) to create 3 clusters using unsupervised Lloyds k-means algorithm. The training should only stop if the difference between the cluster center locations in two consecutive iterations is less than 0.001 or if the number of iterations has reached 1000. For the initial selection of cluster locations choose 3 points from the data set randomly.

kmData = read.csv("kMeansData.csv")

# initialize cluster dentroids
centers = matrix(c(runif(3, 1, 7), runif(3, 0, 2.5), c(1, 2, 3)), nrow=3, ncol=3)

# Assign input values to nearest centroid class labels
CL = function(inputs, centroid){
  
  # initialize storage matrix
  mat = matrix(0, nrow=nrow(inputs), ncol=nrow(centroid))
  
  # calculate euclidean distances of inputs with each centroid
  for (i in 1:nrow(inputs)){
    for (j in 1:nrow(centroid)){
      mat[i, j] = sqrt((inputs[i,1]-centroid[j,1])^2 + (inputs[i,2]-centroid[j,2])^2)
    }
  }
  
  # create a new column; take the min value of each row for that column
  mat = cbind(mat, unlist(apply(mat, 1, min)))
  
  # initialize class label storage vector
  cls = {}
  
  # go through each column of the matrix and match it with the minimum value's column
  # add the vector onto the matrix
  for (i in 1:nrow(mat)){
    mat2 = unlist(match(mat[i,ncol(mat)], mat[i,1:nrow(centroid)]))
    cls = c(cls, mat2)
  }
  mat = cbind(mat, cls)
  return(mat)
}

# calculate true centroids
Cent_Up = function(inputs, centroid){
  
  # initialize S
  S = matrix(0, nrow=nrow(inputs), ncol=(ncol(inputs)))
  
  # just bear with this
  Cent_New = centroid
  
  # calculate and assign distances, combine labels with kmData, iterate through
  for (i in 1:1000){
    dists = CL(inputs, centroid)
    new_data = cbind(inputs, dists[,ncol(dists)])
    
    # set S as subset of distances in k, calculate new centroid
    for (k in 1:nrow(centroid)){
      S = new_data[(new_data[,3] %in% k), 1:2]
      Cent_New[k, 1:2] = colMeans(S)
      
    }
   # set stopping criteria
   if (sum(abs(Cent_New[,1:2] - centroid[,1:2])) < 0.001){
     print(i)
     break
      }
    centroid = Cent_New
  }
  return(centroid)
}

cent2 = Cent_Up(kmData, centers)
## [1] 6
data2 = CL(kmData, cent2)
Classified = cbind(kmData, data2[,5])

After convergence, report the final cluster centers. Plot the 3 clusters in different colors with cluster centers clearly marked on the plot.

X = sqrt((rbf_input[,1] - rbf_input[,2])^2)
ones = rep(1, nrow(rbf_input))

Us = sqrt((Centers2[,1] - Centers[,2])^2)

phi = matrix(c(ones, rbf_mat(X, Us, 0.5)), nrow=20, ncol=3)
y = rbfData[,3]

W3s = solve(t(phi)%*%phi)%*%t(phi)%*%y

yhat = round(hx(phi, W3s), 0)

Acc = mean(yhat == y)

Problem 4 (30 points)

In this problem you will use hold-out validation (80% 20%) to select number of cluster centers for an RBF classifier model. You will be using healthcare- Train.csv and healthcareTest.csv data sets to predict the pdc-80-flag using the following continuous features: total-los, num-op, num-er, num-ndc, pre- total-cost, and pre-CCI.

Setting up the data

healthTrain = read.csv("healthcareTrain.csv")
healthTest = read.csv("healthcareTest.csv")

Train = data.frame(c(healthTrain["total_los"], healthTrain["num_op"],
                     healthTrain["num_er"], healthTrain["num_ndc"],
                     healthTrain["pre_total_cost"], healthTrain["pre_CCI"],
                     healthTrain["pdc_80_flag"]))

Test = data.frame(c(healthTest["total_los"], healthTest["num_op"],
                    healthTest["num_er"], healthTest["num_ndc"],
                    healthTest["pre_total_cost"], healthTest["pre_CCI"],
                    healthTest["pdc_80_flag"]))

TrainFull = data.frame(c(healthTrain["total_los"], healthTrain["num_op"],
                         healthTrain["num_er"], healthTrain["num_ndc"],
                         healthTrain["pre_total_cost"], healthTrain["pre_CCI"],
                         healthTrain["pdc_80_flag"]))

holdout_partition = function(train){
  # randomized integers 1-n, by 20% of n 
  ind = sample(1:dim(train)[1], dim(train)[1]*0.2) 
  for (i in train){
    return(train[ind,]) # return the randomized n*0.2 index values
  }
}

Val = holdout_partition(Train)
Train = Train[-(match(Val[,1], Train[,1])),]

Use rbf function in R to create your RBF model. Try cluster numbers 5 to 25. Use your hold-out validation set to figure out the best number of clusters. Report the best number of clusters and the corresponding validation accuracy rate.

library(RSNNS)
## Loading required package: Rcpp
# AccStore = matrix(0, 20, 1)
AccStore = list()

for (i in 5:25){
  rbf_model = rbf(Train[,1:6], matrix(Train[,7]), size=i, maxit=1000, linOut=FALSE)
  Yhat = round(predict(rbf_model, Val[,1:6]))
  Accuracy = mean(Yhat == Val[,7])
  AccStore[i] = Accuracy
}

BestCentroidNum = which.max(unlist(AccStore))+4
# add 4 because we started our iteration at 5. 

cat('Highest performing centroid numbers: ', BestCentroidNum)
## Highest performing centroid numbers:  15
cat('Corresponding Accuracy: ', AccStore[[BestCentroidNum]])
